About Prophet

Prophet is the industry standard code library for forecasting business time series data. It was developed by engineers as Facebook and is based on a non-linear modular regression model. Prophet parameters are easy to interpret and adjust thus simplifying the process of creating accurate domain-specific forecasts. The Prophet model formulation is:

\(y(t) = g(t) + s(t) + h(t) + \epsilon_{t}\)

where:

\(g(t)\) is the overall time series trend function

\(s(t)\) represents periodic changes (daily, weekly, monthly, and/or yearly seasonality)

\(h(t)\) represents the effects of holidays or other irregular changes

\(\epsilon_{t}\) is the error term

A detailed explanation of Prophet can be found here: https://peerj.com/preprints/3190.pdf

RI Data

The input data for the Prophet Model comes from the RI_POLICY_FACT table which will be housed in APPFDW (pending QA/QC). The basic model requires two variables: the date that the RI policies were issued ISSUED_DATE and the number of new policies NEW_POLICIES. A snapshot of the data is below:

Exploratory Data Analysis

The heatmap shows the number of new RI policies purchased every day from 2017-11-29 until 2022-02-22. It shows that that new policies are not purchased on the weekends, and that the highest number of purchases are towards the beginning and end of each month particularly during leasing season (July-August). These findings will be incorporated into the Prophet model.

Basic Model Formulation

The R code for creating a basic model is shown below:

#create basic model that accounts for observed seasonal trends
z$sat = ifelse(weekdays(as.Date(z$ds)) == 'Saturday',1,0) #we don't see policies on weekends
z$sun = ifelse(weekdays(as.Date(z$ds)) == 'Sunday',1,0)
z$m1 = ifelse(day(z$ds) == 1,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for first of the month
z$m2 = ifelse(day(z$ds) == 2,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for second of the month
z$m31 = ifelse(day(z$ds) == 31,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for 31st of the month
z$m30 = ifelse(day(z$ds) == 30,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for 30th of the month
z$cap = 2000 ##1681 policies is the most we've ever sold in a day -- set cap on 2022 max at 2000 in a day and use logistic growth curve

m <- prophet(seasonality.mode = "multiplicative", growth = "logistic", daily.seasonality = 50, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.5, seasonality.prior.scale = 0.1)
m <- add_regressor(m,'m1')
m <- add_regressor(m,'m2')
m <- add_regressor(m,'m31')
m <- add_regressor(m,'m30')
m <- add_regressor(m,'sat')
m <- add_regressor(m,'sun')
m  = add_country_holidays(m, 'US')
m <- add_seasonality(m, name='monthly', period=30.5, fourier.order=5)
m <- fit.prophet(m, z)

future <- make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 300)
future$sat = ifelse(weekdays(as.Date(future$ds)) == 'Saturday',1,0)
future$sun = ifelse(weekdays(as.Date(future$ds)) == 'Sunday',1,0)
future$m1 = ifelse(day(future$ds) == 1,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for first of the month
future$m2 = ifelse(day(future$ds) == 2,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for second of the month
future$m31 = ifelse(day(future$ds) == 31,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for 31st of the month
future$m30 = ifelse(day(future$ds) == 30,1,0) #add binary dummy variable for 30th of the month
future$cap = 2000

forecast <- predict(m, future)

This plot shows the model output. Black dots represent the actual cumulative total of new policies sold each day, and the dark blue line shows the daily cumulative totals estimated by the model. The light blue region shows the range of model uncertainty.
